The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, July 29, 2004 				 Subsidy turns a drag on ONGC profits
 OUR BUREAUX																								July 28: Oil and Natural Gas Corporation today reported an 8.13 per cent rise in net profit for the first quarter of 2004-05 at Rs 2,308 crore against Rs 2134.54 crore in the corresponding previous fiscal.																								The upstream oil major said the net profit was arrived at after taking into account the government directives to pay Rs 815 crore to oil marketing companies as subsidy for the June quarter of 2004-05. 																								The company would have logged a 31 per cent profit jump had it not been for a Rs 815-crore subsidy pay-out.																								Total income rose to Rs 10,596.33 crore during the reporting quarter from Rs 8,143.07 crore posted a year ago.																								The corporations scrip closed lower at Rs 683.85 on Dalal Street today against yesterdays Rs 701.25.Grasim profit surges																								Grasim Industries Ltd, an Aditya Birla group flagship, has posted a 68 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 219.2 crore for the first quarter of this fiscal against Rs 130.5 crore in the corresponding previous quarter. 																								Total income increased to Rs 1533.34 crore from Rs 1184.48 crore in the April-June quarter of 2003-04, the company said today. Revenues from fibre and pulp business stood at Rs 495.42 crore against Rs 379.43 crore in the year-ago period, it added.																								Cement business chipped in Rs 682.33 crore compared with Rs 573.33 crore in the previous fiscal.Mahindra shines																								Mahindra amp; Mahindra Ltd (M amp;M) has posted a 145 per cent growth in net profit to Rs 103.90 crore in April-June of this fiscal against Rs 42.49 crore in the year-ago period. 																								Gross sales and income from operations stood at Rs 1,686 crore compared with Rs 1,195.1 crore in the first quarter of last fiscal. Net sales and income from operations registered a growth of 42 per cent at Rs 1,423.2 crore.PNB net up 28%																								State-run Punjab National Bank today reported a 28.2 per cent rise in quarterly net profit, boosted by retail loan advances. Net profit for the quarter-ended June 30 of 2004-05 stood at Rs 322.67 crore against Rs 251.76 crore in the corresponding period a year-earlier. 																								Operating profits zoomed 34.7 per cent to Rs 800.99 crore, up from Rs 594.74 crore reported in the year-ago period. 																								Retail advances zoomed 30 per cent to Rs 8,943 crore during the three-month period. 																								The banks capital adequacy ratio, an index to determine a banks financial health, inched up to 12.74 per cent against the Reserve Bank of Indias minimum stipulation of 9 per cent.Gujarat Ambuja net 																								Gujarat Ambuja Cements Ltd has posted a 50 per cent rise in net profit for the fourth quarter ended June 30 at Rs 117.2 crore compared with Rs 78.37 crore in the corresponding previous quarter.																								Total income during the period increased to Rs 588.25 crore from Rs 481.78 crore a year earlier. Net profit for 2003-04 stood at Rs 336.79 crore from Rs 222.09 crore in the previous fiscal. Total income increased to Rs 2018.6 crore (Rs 1,778.55 crore).																								The board has recommended a final dividend of 30 per cent. It had already paid an interim dividend of 50 per cent.
